<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Highest-grossing_franchises_and_film_series">Highest-grossing franchises and film series</h2></div>
<link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1236090951" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">See also: <a href="/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_media_franchises" title="List of highest-grossing media franchises">List of highest-grossing media franchises</a></div>
<p>Prior to 2000, only seven <a href="/wiki/Film_series" title="Film series">film series</a> had grossed over $1 billion at the box office: <i><a href="/wiki/List_of_James_Bond_films" title="List of James Bond films">James Bond</a></i>,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-415"><a href="#cite_note-415"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>100<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/List_of_Star_Wars_films" title="List of Star Wars films">Star Wars</a></i>,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-416"><a href="#cite_note-416"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>101<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/Indiana_Jones" title="Indiana Jones">Indiana Jones</a></i>,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-417"><a href="#cite_note-417"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>102<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <i><a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Rocky_(film_series)" title="Rocky (film series)">Rocky</a></i>,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-418"><a href="#cite_note-418"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>103<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-419"><a href="#cite_note-419"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>104<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-420"><a href="#cite_note-420"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>105<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/Batman_in_film" title="Batman in film">Batman</a></i>,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-421"><a href="#cite_note-421"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>106<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/Jurassic_Park" title="Jurassic Park">Jurassic Park</a></i>,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-422"><a href="#cite_note-422"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>107<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <i><a href="/wiki/List_of_Star_Trek_films" title="List of Star Trek films">Star Trek</a></i>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-423"><a href="#cite_note-423"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>108<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Since the turn of the century, that number has increased to over a hundred.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Numbers_franchises_424-0"><a href="#cite_note-Numbers_franchises-424"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>109<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This is partly due to inflation and market growth, but it is also due to Hollywood's adoption of the <a href="/wiki/Media_franchise" title="Media franchise">franchise</a> model: films that have built-in brand recognition such as being based on a well-known literary source or an established character. The methodology is based on the concept that films associated with things audiences are already familiar with can be more effectively marketed to them, and as such are known as "pre-sold" films within the industry.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-economist_425-0"><a href="#cite_note-economist-425"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>110<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A franchise is typically defined to be at least two works derived from a common <a href="/wiki/Intellectual_property" title="Intellectual property">intellectual property</a>. Traditionally, the work has a tautological relationship with the property, but this is not a prerequisite. An enduring staple of the franchise model is the concept of the <i><a href="/wiki/Crossover_(fiction)" title="Crossover (fiction)">crossover</a></i>, which can be defined as "a story in which characters or concepts from two or more discrete texts or series of texts meet".<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-426"><a href="#cite_note-426"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>111<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A consequence of a crossover is that an intellectual property may be utilized by more than one franchise. For example, <i><a href="/wiki/Batman_v_Superman:_Dawn_of_Justice" title="Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice">Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice</a></i> belongs to not only the <a href="/wiki/Batman" title="Batman">Batman</a> and <a href="/wiki/Superman" title="Superman">Superman</a> franchises, but also to the <a href="/wiki/DC_Extended_Universe" title="DC Extended Universe">DC Extended Universe</a>, which is a <i><a href="/wiki/Shared_universe" title="Shared universe">shared universe</a></i>. A shared universe is a particular type of crossover where a number of characters from a wide range of fictional works wind up sharing a fictional world.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-427"><a href="#cite_note-427"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>112<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The most successful shared universe in the medium of film is the <a href="/wiki/Marvel_Cinematic_Universe" title="Marvel Cinematic Universe">Marvel Cinematic Universe</a>, a crossover between multiple superhero properties owned by <a href="/wiki/Marvel_Comics" title="Marvel Comics">Marvel Comics</a>. The Marvel Cinematic Universe is also the highest-grossing franchise, amassing over $31 billion at the box office.
</p><p>The <i>Spider-Man</i> films are the highest-grossing series based on a single property, earning over $10.6 billion at the box office (although the <a href="/wiki/Eon_Productions" title="Eon Productions">Eon</a> <i>James Bond</i> films have earned over $19 billion in total when adjusted to current prices).<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-429"><a href="#cite_note-429"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Marvel Cinematic Universe has had the most films gross over $1 billion, with eleven. The four <i><a href="/wiki/Avengers_(comics)_in_other_media#Live_action" title="Avengers (comics) in other media">Avengers</a></i> films, the two <i><a href="/wiki/Frozen_(franchise)" title="Frozen (franchise)">Frozen</a></i> films, and the two <i><a href="/wiki/Avatar_(franchise)" title="Avatar (franchise)">Avatar</a></i> films are the only franchises where each installment has grossed over $1 billion, although the <i>Jurassic Park</i>, <i><a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Black_Panther_(film_series)" title="Black Panther (film series)">Black Panther</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Inside_Out_(franchise)" title="Inside Out (franchise)">Inside Out</a></i> series  have averaged over $1 billion per film.
</p>
<dl><dd><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#b6fcb6; color:black;"><span class="legend-text" style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">†</span></span> <i>Background shading indicates that at least one film in the series is playing in the week commencing 13 September 2024 in theaters around the world</i>.</div></dd></dl>

<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1239543626">.mw-parser-output .reflist{margin-bottom:0.5em;list-style-type:decimal}@media screen{.mw-parser-output .reflist{font-size:90%}}.mw-parser-output .reflist .references{font-size:100%;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:inherit}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns-2{column-width:30em}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns-3{column-width:25em}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns{margin-top:0.3em}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns ol{margin-top:0}.mw-parser-output .reflist-columns li{page-break-inside:avoid;break-inside:avoid-column}.mw-parser-output .reflist-upper-alpha{list-style-type:upper-alpha}.mw-parser-output .reflist-upper-roman{list-style-type:upper-roman}.mw-parser-output .reflist-lower-alpha{list-style-type:lower-alpha}.mw-parser-output .reflist-lower-greek{list-style-type:lower-greek}.mw-parser-output .reflist-lower-roman{list-style-type:lower-roman}</style><div class="reflist reflist-lower-alpha">
<div class="mw-references-wrap"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-429"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-429">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Prior to the release of <i>Spectre</i> in 2015, the James Bond series had grossed approximately $17.7 billion at 2015 prices;<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-428"><a href="#cite_note-428"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>113<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> after factoring in earnings of over $1.6 billion from <i>Spectre</i> and <i>No Time to Die</i>, the series has earned at least $19.3 billion adjusted for inflation.</span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>

<li id="cite_note-Cones-125"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Cones_125-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Cones_125-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFCones1997">Cones, John W. (1997). <i>The feature film distribution deal: a critical analysis of the single most important film industry agreement</i>. <a href="/wiki/Southern_Illinois_University_Press" title="Southern Illinois University Press">Southern Illinois University Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=EoeJ7VmwnDIC&amp;pg=PA41" rel="nofollow">41</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8093-2082-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8093-2082-0"><bdi>978-0-8093-2082-0</bdi></a>. <q>Distributor rentals: It is also important to know and recognize the difference between the distributor's gross receipts and the gross rentals. The term "rentals" refers to the aggregate amount of the film distributor's share of monies paid at theatre box offices computed on the basis of negotiated agreements between the distributor and the exhibitor. Note that gross receipts refers to amounts actually received and from all markets and media, whereas gross rentals refers to amounts earned from theatrical exhibition only, regardless of whether received by the distributor. Thus, gross receipts is the much broader term and includes distributor rentals. The issue of film rentals (i.e., what percentage of a film's box office gross comes back to the distributor) is of key importance...More current numbers suggest that distributor rentals for the major studio/distributor released films average in the neighborhood of 43% of box office gross. Again, however, such an average is based on widely divergent distributor rental ratios on individual films.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+feature+film+distribution+deal%3A+a+critical+analysis+of+the+single+most+important+film+industry+agreement&amp;rft.pages=41&amp;rft.pub=Southern+Illinois+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8093-2082-0&amp;rft.aulast=Cones&amp;rft.aufirst=John+W.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Marich-126"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Marich_126-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFMarich2009">Marich, Robert (2009) [1st. pub. <a href="/wiki/Focal_Press" title="Focal Press">Focal Press</a>:2005]. <i>Marketing to moviegoers: a handbook of strategies used by major studios and independents</i> (2 ed.). <a href="/wiki/Southern_Illinois_University_Press" title="Southern Illinois University Press">Southern Illinois University Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=_6USFaYxyeUC&amp;pg=PA252" rel="nofollow">252</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8093-2884-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8093-2884-0"><bdi>978-0-8093-2884-0</bdi></a>. <q>Rentals are the distributors' share of the box office gross and typically set by a complex, two-part contract.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Marketing+to+moviegoers%3A+a+handbook+of+strategies+used+by+major+studios+and+independents&amp;rft.pages=252&amp;rft.edition=2&amp;rft.pub=Southern+Illinois+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8093-2884-0&amp;rft.aulast=Marich&amp;rft.aufirst=Robert&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Balio-127"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Balio_127-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFBalio2005">Balio, Tino (2005). <i>The American film industry</i>. <a href="/wiki/University_of_Wisconsin_Press" title="University of Wisconsin Press">University of Wisconsin Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=OBpDf_uUp30C&amp;pg=PA296" rel="nofollow">296</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-299-09874-2" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-299-09874-2"><bdi>978-0-299-09874-2</bdi></a>. <q>Film Rentals as Percent of Volume of Business (1939): 36.4</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+American+film+industry&amp;rft.pages=296&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Wisconsin+Press&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-299-09874-2&amp;rft.aulast=Balio&amp;rft.aufirst=Tino&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-128"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-128">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFBalio1987">Balio, Tino (1987). <a class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/unitedartistscom00bali/page/124" rel="nofollow"><i>United Artists: the Company that Changed the Film Industry</i></a>. <a href="/wiki/University_of_Wisconsin_Press" title="University of Wisconsin Press">University of Wisconsin Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=9EeK5s3aw44C&amp;pg=PA124" rel="nofollow">124–125</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-299-11440-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-299-11440-4"><bdi>978-0-299-11440-4</bdi></a>. <q>To rekindle interest in the movies, Hollywood not only had to compete with television but also with other leisure-time activities...Movies made a comeback by 1955, but audiences had changed. Moviegoing became a special event for most people, creating the phenomenon of the big picture.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=United+Artists%3A+the+Company+that+Changed+the+Film+Industry&amp;rft.pages=124-125&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Wisconsin+Press&amp;rft.date=1987&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-299-11440-4&amp;rft.aulast=Balio&amp;rft.aufirst=Tino&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Funitedartistscom00bali%2Fpage%2F124&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-HallNeale179-129"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-HallNeale179_129-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFHallNeale2010">Hall &amp; Neale 2010</a>, p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=jhvrSwOOsRgC&amp;pg=PA179" rel="nofollow">179</a>. "Later epics proved far more disastrous for the backers. <a href="/wiki/Samuel_Bronston" title="Samuel Bronston">Samuel Bronston</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/The_Fall_of_the_Roman_Empire_(film)" title="The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)">The Fall of the Roman Empire</a></i>, filmed in Spain, cost $17,816,876 and grossed only $1.9 million in America. George Stevens's long-gestating life of Christ, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Greatest_Story_Ever_Told" title="The Greatest Story Ever Told">The Greatest Story Ever Told</a></i> (1965), which had been in planning since 1954 and in production since 1962, earned domestic rentals of $6,962,715 on a $21,481,745 negative cost, the largest amount yet spent on a production made entirely within the United States. <i><a href="/wiki/The_Bible:_In_the_Beginning..." title="The Bible: In the Beginning...">The Bible: In the Beginning...</a></i> (1966) was financed by the Italian producer <a href="/wiki/Dino_De_Laurentiis" title="Dino De Laurentiis">Dino De Laurentiis</a> from private investors and Swiss banks. He then sold distribution rights outside Italy jointly to <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Twentieth_Century_Fox" title="Twentieth Century Fox">Fox</a> and <a href="/wiki/Seven_Arts_Productions" title="Seven Arts Productions">Seven Arts</a> for $15 million (70 percent of which came from Fox), thereby recouping the bulk of his $18 million investment. Although <i>The Bible</i> returned a respectable world rental of $25.3 million, Fox was still left with a net loss of just over $1.5 million. It was the last biblical epic to be released by any major Hollywood studio for nearly twenty years."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-130"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-130">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation web cs1" id="CITEREFWilliams2015">Williams, Trey (September 25, 2015). <a class="external text" href="http://www.marketwatch.com/story/ridley-scotts-latest-alien-announcement-drives-hollywoods-sequel-problem-2015-09-25" rel="nofollow">"Ridley Scott's latest 'Alien' announcement drives Hollywood's sequel problem"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/MarketWatch" title="MarketWatch">MarketWatch</a></i>. <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160608132003/http://www.marketwatch.com/story/ridley-scotts-latest-alien-announcement-drives-hollywoods-sequel-problem-2015-09-25" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> from the original on June 8, 2016<span class="reference-accessdate">. <li id="cite_note-366"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-366">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFParkinson2007">Parkinson, David (2007). <i>The Rough Guide to Film Musicals</i>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Dorling_Kindersley" title="Dorling Kindersley">Dorling Kindersley</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Zff4BhUOOnwC&amp;pg=PA28" rel="nofollow">28</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-84353-650-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-84353-650-5"><bdi>978-1-84353-650-5</bdi></a>. <q>But they had previously succeeded in showing how musicals could centre on ordinary people with <i>Sunny Side Up</i> (1929), which had grossed $2 million at the box office and demonstrated a new maturity and ingenuity in the staging of story and dance.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Rough+Guide+to+Film+Musicals&amp;rft.pages=28&amp;rft.pub=Dorling+Kindersley&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-84353-650-5&amp;rft.aulast=Parkinson&amp;rft.aufirst=David&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-HallNeale6-367"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-HallNeale6_367-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-HallNeale6_367-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFHallNeale2010">Hall &amp; Neale 2010</a>, pp. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Ro0hASPfC68C&amp;pg=PA6" rel="nofollow">6</a>–<a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Ro0hASPfC68C&amp;pg=PA7" rel="nofollow">7</a>. "For similar reasons of accountability, <i>Variety</i> has typically used figures for domestic (U.S. and Canadian) rather than worldwide revenue. This became its standard policy in 1940, when the advent of war in Europe persuaded the American film industry (temporarily, as it turned out) that it should be wholly reliant on the home market for profitability. Where specific rentals data are reported in <i>Variety</i> before this (which tended to be only sporadically) they were often for worldwide rather domestic performance. This was also the case with other trade sources, such as <i>Quigley</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s annual <i>Motion Picture Almanac</i>, which published its own all-time hits lists from the early 1930s onward. The subsequent confusion of domestic and worldwide figures, and of rental and box-office figures, has plagued many published accounts of Hollywood history (sometimes including those in <i>Variety</i> itself), and we have attempted to be diligant in clarifying the differences between them."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-368"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-368">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFMcBride2011">McBride, Joseph (2011). <i>Frank Capra: The Catastrophe of Success</i>. <a href="/wiki/University_Press_of_Mississippi" title="University Press of Mississippi">University Press of Mississippi</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=DMkLpTFBEtUC&amp;pg=PA309" rel="nofollow">309</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-60473-838-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-60473-838-4"><bdi>978-1-60473-838-4</bdi></a>. <q>According to the studio's books <i>It Happened One Night</i> brought in $1 million in film rentals during its initial release, but as Joe Walker pointed out, the figure would have been much larger if the film had not been sold to theaters on a block-booking basis in a package with more than two dozen lesser Columbia films, and the total rentals of the package spread among them all, as was customary in that era, since it minimized the risk and allowed the major studios to dominate the marketplace.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Frank+Capra%3A+The+Catastrophe+of+Success&amp;rft.pages=309&amp;rft.pub=University+Press+of+Mississippi&amp;rft.date=2011&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-60473-838-4&amp;rft.aulast=McBride&amp;rft.aufirst=Joseph&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>

<li id="cite_note-Dirks_(2010)-375"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Dirks_(2010)_375-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Dirks_(2010)_375-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Dirks_(2010)_375-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Dirks_(2010)_375-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Dirks_(2010)_375-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Dirks_(2010)_375-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation web cs1" id="CITEREFDirks">Dirks, Tim. <a class="external text" href="http://www.filmsite.org/greatfilmssummary.html" rel="nofollow">"Top Films of All-Time: Part 1 – Box-Office Blockbusters"</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Filmsite.org" title="Filmsite.org">Filmsite.org</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. <li id="cite_note-Wasko-376"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Wasko_376-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Wasko_376-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFWasko1986">Wasko, Janet (1986). "D.W. Griffiths and the banks: a case study in film financing". In Kerr, Paul (ed.). <i>The Hollywood Film Industry: A Reader</i>. <a href="/wiki/Routledge" title="Routledge">Routledge</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=jMINAAAAQAAJ&amp;pg=PA34" rel="nofollow">34</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7100-9730-9" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7100-9730-9"><bdi>978-0-7100-9730-9</bdi></a>. <q>Various accounts have cited $15 to $18 million profits during the first few years of release, while in a letter to a potential investor in the proposed sound version, Aitken noted that a $15 to $18 million box-office gross was a 'conservative estimate'. For years <i>Variety</i> has listed <i>The Birth of a Nation</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s total rental at $50 million. (This reflects the total amount paid to the distributor, not box-office gross.) This 'trade legend' has finally been acknowledged by <i>Variety</i> as a 'whopper myth', and the amount has been revised to $5 million. That figure seems far more feasible, as reports of earnings in the Griffith collection list gross receipts for 1915–1919 at slightly more than $5.2 million (including foreign distribution) and total earnings after deducting general office expenses, but not royalties, at about $2 million.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=D.W.+Griffiths+and+the+banks%3A+a+case+study+in+film+financing&amp;rft.btitle=The+Hollywood+Film+Industry%3A+A+Reader&amp;rft.pages=34&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft.date=1986&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7100-9730-9&amp;rft.aulast=Wasko&amp;rft.aufirst=Janet&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Variety_(1932)-377"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Variety_(1932)_377-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation magazine cs1"><a class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/variety106-1932-06/page/n120/mode/1up" rel="nofollow">"Biggest Money Pictures"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Variety_(magazine)" title="Variety (magazine)">Variety</a></i>. <li id="cite_note-378"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-378">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation news cs1">"<span class="cs1-kern-left"></span>'Peter Pan' flies again". <i><a href="/wiki/Daily_Record_(Washington)" title="Daily Record (Washington)">Daily Record</a></i>. Ellensburg, Washington. <a href="/wiki/United_Press_International" title="United Press International">United Press International</a>. July 21, 1989. p. <a class="external text" href="https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=r3dUAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=WY8DAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=2540,2188129" rel="nofollow">16</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Daily+Record&amp;rft.atitle=%27Peter+Pan%27+flies+again&amp;rft.pages=16&amp;rft.date=1989-07-21&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>

<li id="cite_note-379"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-379">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFBlockWilson2010">Block &amp; Wilson 2010</a>, p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;pg=PA237" rel="nofollow">237</a>. "By the end of 1938, it had grossed more than $8 million in worldwide rentals and was ranked at the time as the second-highest-grossing film after the 1925 epic <i>Ben-Hur</i>".</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-380"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-380">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFFinler2003">Finler 2003</a>, p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=rvVhEJmbfrsC&amp;pg=PA47" rel="nofollow">47</a>. "Walt Disney took a big risk when he decided to invest $1.5 million in his first feature-length animated film, <i>Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs</i>. It became the biggest hit of the sound era and the largest-grossing movie since <i>The Birth of a Nation</i> – until the release of independent producer David O. Selznick's <i>Gone with the Wind</i> just two years later."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-381"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-381">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFBarrios1995">Barrios, Richard (1995). <a class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/songindarkbirtho00barr/page/49" rel="nofollow"><i>A Song in the Dark: The Birth of the Musical Film</i></a>. <a href="/wiki/Oxford_University_Press" title="Oxford University Press">Oxford University Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/songindarkbirtho00barr/page/49" rel="nofollow">49</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-19-508811-3" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-19-508811-3"><bdi>978-0-19-508811-3</bdi></a>. <q>Since it's rarely seen today, <i>The Singing Fool</i> is frequently confused with <i>The Jazz Singer</i>; although besides Jolson and a pervasively maudlin air the two have little in common. In the earlier film Jolson was inordinately attached to his mother and sang "Mammy"; here the fixation was on his young son, and "Sonny Boy" became an enormous hit. So did the film, which amassed a stunning world-wide gross of $5.9 million...Some sources give it as the highest gross of <i>any</i> film in its initial release prior to <i>Gone with the Wind</i>. This is probably overstating it—MGM's records show that <i>Ben-Hur</i> and <i>The Big Parade</i> grossed more, and no one knows just how much <i>The Birth of a Nation</i> brought in. Still, by the standards of the time it's an amazing amount.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+Song+in+the+Dark%3A+The+Birth+of+the+Musical+Film&amp;rft.pages=49&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1995&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-508811-3&amp;rft.aulast=Barrios&amp;rft.aufirst=Richard&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Fsongindarkbirtho00barr%2Fpage%2F49&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-382"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-382">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFEverson1998">Everson, William K. (1998) [First published 1978]. <a class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/americansilentfi00ever_0/page/374" rel="nofollow"><i>American silent film</i></a>. <a href="/wiki/Da_Capo_Press" title="Da Capo Press">Da Capo Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=pyQaKxBjjzMC&amp;pg=PA374" rel="nofollow">374</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-306-80876-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-306-80876-0"><bdi>978-0-306-80876-0</bdi></a>. <q>Putting <i>The Birth of a Nation</i> in fifth place is open to question, since it is generally conceded to be the top-grossing film of all time. However, it has always been difficult to obtain reliable box-office figures for this film, and it may have been even more difficult in the mid-1930s. After listing it until the mid-1970s as <i>the</i> top-grosser, though finding it impossible to quote exact figures, <i>Variety</i>, the trade journal, suddenly repudiated the claim but without giving specific details or reasons. On the basis of the number of paid admissions, and <i>continuous</i> exhibition, its number one position seems justified.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=American+silent+film&amp;rft.pages=374&amp;rft.pub=Da+Capo+Press&amp;rft.date=1998&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-306-80876-0&amp;rft.aulast=Everson&amp;rft.aufirst=William+K.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Famericansilentfi00ever_0%2Fpage%2F374&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-HallNeale163-383"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-HallNeale163_383-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFHallNeale2010">Hall &amp; Neale 2010</a>, p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=jhvrSwOOsRgC&amp;pg=PA163" rel="nofollow">163</a>. "MGM's silent <i>Ben-Hur</i>, which opened at the end of 1925, had out-grossed all the other pictures released by the company in 1926 combined. With worldwide rentals of $9,386,000 on first release it was, with the sole possible exception of <i>The Birth of a Nation</i>, the highest-earning film of the entire silent era."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-du_Brow-384"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-du_Brow_384-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-du_Brow_384-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation news cs1" id="CITEREFdu_Brow1965">du Brow, Rick (September 22, 1965). <li id="cite_note-387"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-387">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFKlopschSandisonTalmage1965">Klopsch, Louis; Sandison, George Henry; Talmage, Thomas De Witt (1965). <i><a href="/wiki/Christian_Herald" title="Christian Herald">Christian Herald</a></i>. <li id="cite_note-HallNeale160-388"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-HallNeale160_388-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFHallNeale2010">Hall &amp; Neale 2010</a>, pp. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=jhvrSwOOsRgC&amp;pg=PA160" rel="nofollow">160–161</a>. "General release began at normal prices in 1959 and continued until the end of the following year, when the film was temporarily withdrawn (the first of several reissues came in 1966). The worldwide rental by this time was around $60 million. In the domestic market it dislodged <i>Gone with the Wind</i> from the number one position on <i>Variety</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s list of All-Time Rentals Champs. <i>GWTW</i> had hitherto maintained its lead through several reissues (and was soon to regain it through another in 1961)."</span>

<li id="cite_note-Bartel-397"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Bartel_397-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFBartel1989">Bartel, Pauline (1989). <a class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/completegonewith00bart/page/127" rel="nofollow"><i>The Complete Gone with the Wind Trivia Book: The Movie and More</i></a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Taylor_Trade_Publishing" title="Taylor Trade Publishing">Taylor Trade Publishing</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=ZJLb5GC35E8C&amp;pg=PA127" rel="nofollow">127</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-87833-619-7" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-87833-619-7"><bdi>978-0-87833-619-7</bdi></a>. <q>At the end of the 1941 general release, MGM decided to withdraw GWTW again. The prints were battered, but the studio believed one final fling for GWTW was possible. The film returned to movie theaters for the third time in the spring of 1942 and stayed in release until late 1943 ... When MGM finally pulled the film from exhibition, all worn-out prints were destroyed, and GWTW was at last declared out of circulation. MGM, which by then had sole ownership of the film, announced that GWTW had grossed over $32 million.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Complete+Gone+with+the+Wind+Trivia+Book%3A+The+Movie+and+More&amp;rft.pages=127&amp;rft.pub=Taylor+Trade+Publishing&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-87833-619-7&amp;rft.aulast=Bartel&amp;rft.aufirst=Pauline&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Fcompletegonewith00bart%2Fpage%2F127&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>

<li id="cite_note-Cook_(2002)-407"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Cook_(2002)_407-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1 cs1-prop-long-vol" id="CITEREFCook2002">Cook, David A. (2002). <i>Lost Illusions: American Cinema in the Shadow of Watergate and Vietnam, 1970–1979</i>. Vol. 9 of History of the American Cinema, Charles Harpole. <a href="/wiki/University_of_California_Press" title="University of California Press">University of California Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=HVygqYMVP2wC&amp;pg=PA50" rel="nofollow">50</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-520-23265-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-520-23265-5"><bdi>978-0-520-23265-5</bdi></a>. <q>The industry was stunned when <i>Star Wars</i> earned nearly $3 million in its first week and by the end of August had grossed $100 million; it played continuously throughout 1977–1978, and was officially re-released in 1978 and 1979, by the end of which it had earned $262 million in rentals worldwide to become the top-grossing film of all time – a position it would maintain until surpassed by Universal's <i>E.T.: The Extra-Terrestrial</i> in January 1983.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Lost+Illusions%3A+American+Cinema+in+the+Shadow+of+Watergate+and+Vietnam%2C+1970%E2%80%931979&amp;rft.pages=50&amp;rft.pub=University+of+California+Press&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-520-23265-5&amp;rft.aulast=Cook&amp;rft.aufirst=David+A.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>

<li id="cite_note-134"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-134">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFMonaco2009">Monaco, James (2009). <i>How to Read a Film:Movies, Media, and Beyond</i>. <a href="/wiki/Oxford_University_Press" title="Oxford University Press">Oxford University Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=bgbOsjnppAcC&amp;pg=PA262" rel="nofollow">262</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-19-975579-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-19-975579-0"><bdi>978-0-19-975579-0</bdi></a>. <q>The Birth of a Nation, costing an unprecedented and, many believed, thoroughly foolhardy $110,000, eventually returned $20 million and more. The actual figure is hard to calculate because the film was distributed on a "states' rights" basis in which licenses to show the film were sold outright. The actual cash generated by The Birth of a Nation may have been as much as $50 million to $100 million, an almost inconceivable amount for such an early film.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=How+to+Read+a+Film%3AMovies%2C+Media%2C+and+Beyond&amp;rft.pages=262&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-975579-0&amp;rft.aulast=Monaco&amp;rft.aufirst=James&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Wasko-135"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Wasko_135-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Wasko_135-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFWasko1986">Wasko, Janet (1986). "D.W. Griffiths and the banks: a case study in film financing". In Kerr, Paul (ed.). <i>The Hollywood Film Industry: A Reader</i>. <a href="/wiki/Routledge" title="Routledge">Routledge</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=jMINAAAAQAAJ&amp;pg=PA34" rel="nofollow">34</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7100-9730-9" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7100-9730-9"><bdi>978-0-7100-9730-9</bdi></a>. <q>Various accounts have cited $15 to $18 million profits during the first few years of release, while in a letter to a potential investor in the proposed sound version, Aitken noted that a $15 to $18 million box-office gross was a 'conservative estimate'. For years <i>Variety</i> has listed <i>The Birth of a Nation</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s total rental at $50 million. (This reflects the total amount paid to the distributor, not box-office gross.) This 'trade legend' has finally been acknowledged by <i>Variety</i> as a 'whopper myth', and the amount has been revised to $5 million. That figure seems far more feasible, as reports of earnings in the Griffith collection list gross receipts for 1915–1919 at slightly more than $5.2 million (including foreign distribution) and total earnings after deducting general office expenses, but not royalties, at about $2 million.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=D.W.+Griffiths+and+the+banks%3A+a+case+study+in+film+financing&amp;rft.btitle=The+Hollywood+Film+Industry%3A+A+Reader&amp;rft.pages=34&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft.date=1986&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7100-9730-9&amp;rft.aulast=Wasko&amp;rft.aufirst=Janet&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>

<li id="cite_note-Solomon_(2011)-144"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Solomon_(2011)_144-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Solomon_(2011)_144-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFSolomon2011">Solomon, Aubrey (2011). <i>The Fox Film Corporation, 1915–1935: A History and Filmography</i>. <a href="/wiki/McFarland_%26_Company" title="McFarland &amp; Company">McFarland &amp; Company</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7864-6286-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7864-6286-5"><bdi>978-0-7864-6286-5</bdi></a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Fox+Film+Corporation%2C+1915%E2%80%931935%3A+A+History+and+Filmography&amp;rft.pub=McFarland+%26+Company&amp;rft.date=2011&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7864-6286-5&amp;rft.aulast=Solomon&amp;rft.aufirst=Aubrey&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span>
<ul><li><i>Way Down East</i>: p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=zospQ7o5u0oC&amp;pg=PA52" rel="nofollow">52</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404001622/https://books.google.com/books?id=zospQ7o5u0oC&amp;pg=PA52" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "D.W. Griffith's <i>Way Down East</i> (1920) was projected to return rentals of $4,000,000 on an $800,000 negative. This figure was based on the amounts earned from its roadshow run, coupled with its playoff in the rest of the country's theaters. Griffith had originally placed the potential film rental at $3,000,000 but, because of the success of the various roadshows that were running the $4,000,000 total was expected. The film showed a profit of $615,736 after just 23 weeks of release on a gross of $2,179,613."</li>
<li><i>What Price Glory?</i>: p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=zospQ7o5u0oC&amp;q=What%20Price%20Glory%20hit%20the%20jackpot%20with%20massive%20world%20rentals%20of%20%242%2C429%2C000%2C%20the%20highest%20figure%20in%20the%20history%20of%20the%20company.%20Since%20it%20was%20also%20the%20most%20expensive%20production%20of%20the%20year%20at%20%24817%2C000%20the%20profit%20was%20still%20a%20healthy%20%24796%2C000&amp;pg=PA122" rel="nofollow">112</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404001729/https://books.google.com/books?id=zospQ7o5u0oC&amp;q=What%20Price%20Glory%20hit%20the%20jackpot%20with%20massive%20world%20rentals%20of%20$2,429,000,%20the%20highest%20figure%20in%20the%20history%20of%20the%20company.%20Since%20it%20was%20also%20the%20most%20expensive%20production%20of%20the%20year%20at%20$817,000%20the%20profit%20was%20still%20a%20healthy%20$796,000&amp;pg=PA122" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "What Price Glory hit the jackpot with massive world rentals of $2,429,000, the highest figure in the history of the company. Since it was also the most expensive production of the year at $817,000 the profit was still a healthy $796,000..."</li>
<li><i>Cavalcade</i>: p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=zospQ7o5u0oC&amp;pg=PA170" rel="nofollow">170</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404001726/https://books.google.com/books?id=zospQ7o5u0oC&amp;pg=PA170" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "The actual cost of <i>Cavalcade</i> was $1,116,000 and it was most definitely not guaranteed a success. In fact, if its foreign grosses followed the usual 40 percent of domestic returns, the film would have lost money. In a turnaround, the foreign gross was almost double the $1,000,000 domestic take to reach total world rentals of $3,000,000 and Fox's largest profit of the year at $664,000."</li>
<li><i>State Fair</i>: p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=zospQ7o5u0oC&amp;pg=PA170" rel="nofollow">170</a> . "<i>State Fair</i> did turn out to be a substantial hit with the help of Janet Gaynor boosting Will Rogers back to the level of money-making star. Its prestige engagements helped raked in a total $1,208,000 in domestic rentals. Surprisingly, in foreign countries unfamiliar with state fairs, it still earned a respectable $429,000. With its total rentals, the film ended up showing a $398,000 profit."</li></ul>
</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-145"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-145">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFHallNeale2010">Hall &amp; Neale 2010</a>, p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Ro0hASPfC68C&amp;pg=PA53" rel="nofollow">53</a>. "<i>The Four Forsemen of the Apocalypse</i> was to become Metro's most expensive production and one of the decade's biggest box-office hits. Its production costs have been estimated at "something between $600,000 and $800,000." <i>Variety</i> estimated its worldwide gross at $4 million in 1925 and at $5 million in 1944; in 1991, it estimated its cumulative domestic rentals at $3,800,000."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-146"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-146">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFBrownlow1968">Brownlow, Kevin (1968). <i>The parade's gone by </i>. <a href="/wiki/University_of_California_Press" title="University of California Press">University of California Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=wCD5EH64Qw8C&amp;pg=PA255" rel="nofollow">255</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-520-03068-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-520-03068-8"><bdi>978-0-520-03068-8</bdi></a>. <q>The negative cost was about $986,000, which did not include Fairbanks' own salary. Once the exploitation and release prints were taken into account, <i>Robin Hood</i> cost about $1,400,000—exceeding both <i>Intolerance</i> ($700,000) and the celebrated "million dollar movie" <i>Foolish Wives</i>. But it earned $2,500,000.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+parade%27s+gone+by+..&amp;rft.pages=255&amp;rft.pub=University+of+California+Press&amp;rft.date=1968&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-520-03068-8&amp;rft.aulast=Brownlow&amp;rft.aufirst=Kevin&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-147"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-147">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFVance2008">Vance, Jeffrey (2008). <i>Douglas Fairbanks</i>. <a href="/wiki/University_of_California_Press" title="University of California Press">University of California Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=e3DVBxGQ95YC&amp;pg=PA146" rel="nofollow">146</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-520-25667-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-520-25667-5"><bdi>978-0-520-25667-5</bdi></a>. <q>The film had a production cost of $930,042.78—more than the cost of D.W. <li id="cite_note-151"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-151">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFRobertson1991">Robertson, Patrick (1991). <i>Guinness Book of Movie Facts and Feats</i> (4 ed.). <a href="/wiki/Abbeville_Publishing_Group" title="Abbeville Publishing Group">Abbeville Publishing Group</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=jdjsQY5qkbEC&amp;q=%22samson+and+delilah%22+worldwide+million+rentals" rel="nofollow">30</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-55859-236-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-55859-236-0"><bdi>978-1-55859-236-0</bdi></a>. <q>The top grossing silent film was King Vidor's <i>The Big Parade</i> (US 25), with worldwide rentals of $22 million.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Guinness+Book+of+Movie+Facts+and+Feats&amp;rft.pages=30&amp;rft.edition=4&amp;rft.pub=Abbeville+Publishing+Group&amp;rft.date=1991&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-55859-236-0&amp;rft.aulast=Robertson&amp;rft.aufirst=Patrick&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>

"Even then, at a time when the budget for a feature averaged at around $300,000, no more than $382,000 was spent on production...According to the Eddie Mannix Ledger at MGM, it grossed $4,990,000 domestically and $1,141,000 abroad."</span>

<li id="cite_note-Ben-Hur_(1925)-153"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Ben-Hur_(1925)_153-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation web cs1"><a class="external text" href="http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/35/Ben-Hur/notes.html" rel="nofollow">"Ben-Hur (1925) – Notes"</a>. <a href="/wiki/Turner_Classic_Movies" title="Turner Classic Movies">Turner Classic Movies</a>. <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20190724083359/http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/35/Ben-Hur/notes.html" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> from the original on July 24, 2019<span class="reference-accessdate">. <li id="cite_note-HallNeale163-154"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-HallNeale163_154-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFHallNeale2010">Hall &amp; Neale 2010</a>, p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=jhvrSwOOsRgC&amp;pg=PA163" rel="nofollow">163</a>. "MGM's silent <i>Ben-Hur</i>, which opened at the end of 1925, had out-grossed all the other pictures released by the company in 1926 combined. With worldwide rentals of $9,386,000 on first release it was, with the sole possible exception of <i>The Birth of a Nation</i>, the highest-earning film of the entire silent era. (At a negative cost of $3,967,000, it was also the most expensive.)"</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-155"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-155">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation web cs1" id="CITEREFMiller">Miller, Frank. <a class="external text" href="http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/410794/For-Heaven-s-Sake/articles.html" rel="nofollow">"For Heaven's Sake (1926) – Articles"</a>. <a href="/wiki/Turner_Classic_Movies" title="Turner Classic Movies">Turner Classic Movies</a>. <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20190724090237/http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/410794/For-Heaven-s-Sake/articles.html" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> from the original on July 24, 2019<span class="reference-accessdate">. <li id="cite_note-156"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-156">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFFinler2003">Finler 2003</a>, p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=rvVhEJmbfrsC&amp;q=wings+%242+million&amp;pg=PA188" rel="nofollow">188</a>. "At a cost of $2 million <i>Wings</i> was the studio's most expensive movie of the decade, and though it did well it was not good enough to earn a profit."</span>

<li id="cite_note-Jolson-157"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Jolson_157-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Jolson_157-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>The Jazz Singer</i> and <i>The Singing Fool</i>
<ul><li><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation cs2" id="CITEREFBlock2010">Block, Hayley Taylor (2010), <i>The Jazz Singer</i>, p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;pg=PA113" rel="nofollow">113</a>, <q>The film brought in $2.6 million in worldwide rentals and made a net profit of $1,196,750. Jolson's follow-up Warner Bros. film, <i>The Singing Fool</i> (1928), brought in over two times as much, with $5.9 in worldwide rentals and a profit of $3,649,000, making them two of the most profitable films in the 1920s.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Jazz+Singer&amp;rft.pages=113&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.aulast=Block&amp;rft.aufirst=Hayley+Taylor&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span> In: <a href="#CITEREFBlockWilson2010">Block &amp; Wilson 2010</a>.</li></ul>
</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Crafton-158"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Crafton_158-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFCrafton1999">Crafton, Donald (1999). <i>The Talkies: American Cinema's Transition to Sound, 1926–1931</i>. <a href="/wiki/University_of_California_Press" title="University of California Press">University of California Press</a>. pp. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=KFB_oT-jupQC&amp;pg=PA549" rel="nofollow">549</a>–552. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-520-22128-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-520-22128-4"><bdi>978-0-520-22128-4</bdi></a>. <q><i>The Singing Fool</i>: Negative Cost ($1000s): 388</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Talkies%3A+American+Cinema%27s+Transition+to+Sound%2C+1926%E2%80%931931&amp;rft.pages=549-552&amp;rft.pub=University+of+California+Press&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-520-22128-4&amp;rft.aulast=Crafton&amp;rft.aufirst=Donald&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>

<li id="cite_note-bradley-160"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-bradley_160-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFBradley2004">Bradley, Edwin M. (2004) [1st. pub. 1996]. <i>The First Hollywood Musicals: A Critical Filmography of 171 Features, 1927 Through 1932</i>. <a href="/wiki/McFarland_%26_Company" title="McFarland &amp; Company">McFarland &amp; Company</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7864-2029-2" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7864-2029-2"><bdi>978-0-7864-2029-2</bdi></a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+First+Hollywood+Musicals%3A+A+Critical+Filmography+of+171+Features%2C+1927+Through+1932&amp;rft.pub=McFarland+%26+Company&amp;rft.date=2004&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7864-2029-2&amp;rft.aulast=Bradley&amp;rft.aufirst=Edwin+M.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span>
<ul><li><i>The Singing Fool</i>: p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Rg-UBJaPD-sC&amp;pg=PA12" rel="nofollow">12</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404001730/https://books.google.com/books?id=Rg-UBJaPD-sC&amp;pg=PA12" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "Ego aside, Jolson was at the top of his powers in <i>The Singing Fool</i>. The $150,000 Warner Bros. paid him to make it, and the $388,000 it took to produce the film, were drops in the hat next to the film's world gross of $5.9 million. Its $3.8-million gross in this country set a box-office record that would not be surpassed until Walt Disney's <i>Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs</i> (1937)."</li>
<li><i>The Broadway Melody</i>: p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Rg-UBJaPD-sC&amp;pg=PA24" rel="nofollow">24</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404044842/https://books.google.com/books?id=Rg-UBJaPD-sC&amp;pg=PA24" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "<i>The Broadway Melody</i> with a negative cost of $379,000, grossed $2.8 million in the United States, $4.8 million worldwide, and made a recorded profit of $1.6 million for MGM."</li>
<li><i>Gold Diggers of Broadway</i>: p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Rg-UBJaPD-sC&amp;q=%22gold%20diggers%20of%20broadway%22%20worldwide" rel="nofollow">58</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404001730/https://books.google.com/books?id=Rg-UBJaPD-sC&amp;q=%22gold%20diggers%20of%20broadway%22%20worldwide" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "It grossed an impressive $2.5 million domestically and nearly $4 million worldwide."</li></ul>

<li id="cite_note-Balio_(1996)-164"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Balio_(1996)_164-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Balio_(1996)_164-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1 cs1-prop-long-vol" id="CITEREFBalio1996">Balio, Tino (1996). <i>Grand Design: Hollywood as a Modern Business Enterprise, 1930–1939</i>. <ul><li><i>Cavalcade</i>: p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=_J9HTLOI08wC&amp;pg=PA182" rel="nofollow">182</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404044843/https://books.google.com/books?id=_J9HTLOI08wC&amp;pg=PA182" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "Produced by Winfield Sheehan at a cost of $1.25 million, <i>Cavalcade</i> won Academy Awards for best picture, director, art direction and grossed close to $4 million during its first release, much of which came from Great Britain and the Empire."</li>
<li><i>Whoopee</i>: p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=_J9HTLOI08wC&amp;pg=PA212" rel="nofollow">212</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404001724/https://books.google.com/books?id=_J9HTLOI08wC&amp;pg=PA212" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "Produced by Sam Goldwyn at a cost of $1 million, the picture was an adaptation of a smash musical comedy built around Eddie Cantor...A personality-centered musical, <i>Whoopee!</i> made little attempt to integrate the comedy routines, songs, and story. Nonetheless, Cantor's feature-film debut grossed over $2.6 million worldwide and started a popular series that included <i>Palmy Days</i> (1931), <i>The Kid from Spain</i> (1932), and <i>Roman Scandals</i> (1933)."</li></ul>

<li id="cite_note-Balio_(1976)-165"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Balio_(1976)_165-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>Hell's Angels</i>
<ul><li><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFBalio1976">Balio, Tino (1976). <i>United Artists: The Company Built by the Stars</i>. <a href="/wiki/University_of_Wisconsin_Press" title="University of Wisconsin Press">University of Wisconsin Press</a>. p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=QljKdIYzncoC&amp;pg=PA110" rel="nofollow">110</a>. <q>Hughes did not have the "Midas touch" the trade press so often attributed to him. <i>Variety</i>, for example, reported that <i>Hell's Angels</i> cost $3.2 million to make, and by July, 1931, eight months after its release, the production cost had nearly been paid off. Keats claimed the picture cost $4 million to make and that it earned twice that much within twenty years. The production cost estimate is probably correct. Hughes worked on the picture for over two years, shooting it first as a silent and then as a talkie. Lewis Milestone said that in between Hughes experimented with shooting it in color as well. But <i>Variety</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s earnings report must be the fabrication of a delirious publicity agent, and Keats' the working of a myth maker. During the seven years it was in United Artists distribution, <i>Hell's Angels</i> grossed $1.6 million in the domestic market, of which Hughes' share was $1.2 million. Whatever the foreign gross was, it seems unlikely that it was great enough to earn a profit for the picture.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=United+Artists%3A+The+Company+Built+by+the+Stars&amp;rft.pages=110&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Wisconsin+Press&amp;rft.date=1976&amp;rft.aulast=Balio&amp;rft.aufirst=Tino&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></li></ul>
</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-166"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-166">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation web cs1" id="CITEREFFeaster">Feaster, Felicia. <a class="external text" href="http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/373967%7C18617/Frankenstein.html" rel="nofollow">"Frankenstein (1931)"</a>. <a href="/wiki/Turner_Classic_Movies" title="Turner Classic Movies">Turner Classic Movies</a>. <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20141221174009/http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/373967%7C18617/Frankenstein.html" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> from the original on December 21, 2014<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">July 4,</span> 2011</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Frankenstein+%281931%29&amp;rft.pub=Turner+Classic+Movies&amp;rft.aulast=Feaster&amp;rft.aufirst=Felicia&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.tcm.com%2Fthis-month%2Farticle%2F373967%257C18617%2FFrankenstein.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>

<li id="cite_note-Snow_White_&amp;_Pinocchio-182"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Snow_White_&amp;_Pinocchio_182-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Snow_White_&amp;_Pinocchio_182-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs</i> and <i>Pinocchio</i>
<ul><li><a href="#CITEREFBlockWilson2010">Block &amp; Wilson 2010</a></li></ul>
<dl><dd><dl><dd>p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;q=When%20the%20budget%20rose%20from%20%24250%2C000%20to%20%241%2C488%2C423&amp;pg=PA207" rel="nofollow">207</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404050856/https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;q=When%20the%20budget%20rose%20from%20$250,000%20to%20$1,488,423&amp;pg=PA207" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "When the budget rose from $250,000 to $1,488,423 he even mortgaged his own home and automobile. Disney had bet more than his company on the success of <i>Snow White</i>."</dd>
<dd>p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;q=%22%248%20million%20in%20worldwide%20rentals%22%20george%20lucas%20blockbusting&amp;pg=PA237" rel="nofollow">237</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404001733/https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;q=%22$8%20million%20in%20worldwide%20rentals%22%20george%20lucas%20blockbusting&amp;pg=PA237" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "By the end of 1938, it had grossed more than $8 million in worldwide rentals and was ranked at the time as the second-highest-grossing film after the 1925 epic <i>Ben-Hur</i>".</dd>
<dd>p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;q=%22foreign%20rentals%22&amp;pg=PA255" rel="nofollow">255</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230403234803/https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;q=%22foreign%20rentals%22&amp;pg=PA255" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 3, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "On its initial release <i>Pinocchio</i> brought in only $1.6 million in domestic rentals (compared with <i>Snow White</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s $4.2 million) and $1.9 million in foreign rentals (compared with <i>Snow White</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s $4.3 million)."</dd></dl></dd></dl>

<li id="cite_note-Disney-198"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Disney_198-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Disney_198-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Disney_198-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Disney_198-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFBlockWilson2010">Block &amp; Wilson 2010</a>, pp. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;pg=PA712" rel="nofollow">712–713</a>.

<li id="cite_note-199"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-199">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFGlancy1999">Glancy, Mark (1999). <i>When Hollywood Loved Britain: The Hollywood 'British' Film 1939–1945</i>. <a href="/wiki/Manchester_University_Press" title="Manchester University Press">Manchester University Press</a>. pp. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=T_Yryky_eA4C&amp;pg=PA94" rel="nofollow">94</a>–<a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=T_Yryky_eA4C&amp;pg=PA95" rel="nofollow">95</a>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7190-4853-1" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7190-4853-1"><bdi>978-0-7190-4853-1</bdi></a>. <q><i>Mrs Miniver</i> was a phenomenon. It was the most popular film of the year (from any studio) in both North America and Britain, and its foreign earnings were three times higher than those of any other MGM film released in the 1941–42 season. The production cost ($1,344,000) was one of the highest of the season, indicating the studio never thought of the film as a potential loss-maker. When the film earned a worldwide gross of $8,878,000, MGM had the highest profit ($4,831,000) in its history. <i>Random Harvest</i> nearly matched the success of <i>Mrs Miniver</i> with worldwide earnings of $8,147,000 yielding the second-highest profit in MGM's history ($4,384,000). <i>Random Harvest</i> was also the most popular film of the year in Britain, where it proved to be even more popular than Britain's most acclaimed war film, <i>In Which We Serve</i>.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=When+Hollywood+Loved+Britain%3A+The+Hollywood+%27British%27+Film+1939%E2%80%931945&amp;rft.pages=94-95&amp;rft.pub=Manchester+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7190-4853-1&amp;rft.aulast=Glancy&amp;rft.aufirst=Mark&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-200"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-200">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFBlockWilson2010">Block &amp; Wilson 2010</a>
<ul><li><i>Mrs. Miniver</i>: <link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation cs2" id="CITEREFBurns2010">Burns, Douglas (2010), <i>Mrs. Miniver</i>, p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;pg=PA279" rel="nofollow">279</a>, <q><i>Mrs. Miniver</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s galvanizing effect on Americans spawned a record-breaking ten-week run at Radio City Music Hall and garnered a $5.4 million take in domestic rentals (making <i>Mrs. Miniver</i> 1942's top grosser), with a $4.8 million profit on worldwide rentals of $8.9 million.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Mrs.+Miniver&amp;rft.pages=279&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.aulast=Burns&amp;rft.aufirst=Douglas&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></li>
<li><i>Yankee Doodle Dandy</i>: p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;q=%22worldwide+rentals%22&amp;pg=PA275" rel="nofollow">275</a> <a class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230404001735/https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;q=%22worldwide+rentals%22&amp;pg=PA275" rel="nofollow">Archived</a> April 4, 2023, at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>. "It became the second biggest box-office hit of 1942 (after Mrs. Miniver) and was praised by critics, making a profit of $3.4 million on worldwide rentals of $6.5 million."</li></ul>
</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-201"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-201">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation cs2" id="CITEREFMcAdams2010">McAdams, Frank (2010), <i>For Whom the Bell Tolls</i>, p. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=vpbuSXSSqdkC&amp;pg=PA287" rel="nofollow">287</a>, <q>Despite the early furor over the novel being "pro-red and immoral," the film opened to strong and favorable reviews and brought in $11 million in worldwide rentals in its initial release.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=For+Whom+the+Bell+Tolls&amp;rft.pages=287&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.aulast=McAdams&amp;rft.aufirst=Frank&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span> In: <a href="#CITEREFBlockWilson2010">Block &amp; Wilson 2010</a>.</span>

<li id="cite_note-Schaefer_(1999)-209"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Schaefer_(1999)_209-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFSchaefer1999">Schaefer, Eric (1999). <i>"Bold! Daring! Shocking! True!": A History of Exploitation Films, 1919–1959</i>. <a href="/wiki/Duke_University_Press" title="Duke University Press">Duke University Press</a>. pp. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=CSBZqe0zPaMC&amp;pg=PA197" rel="nofollow">197</a>–199. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8223-2374-7" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8223-2374-7"><bdi>978-0-8223-2374-7</bdi></a>. <q>Leading the pack of postwar sex hygiene films was <i>Mom and Dad</i> (1944), which would become not only the most successful sex hygiene film in history but the biggest pre-1960 exploitation film of any kind. At the end of 1947, the <i>Los Angeles Times</i> reported that <i>Mom and Dad</i> had grossed $2 million. By 1949 <i>Time</i> had estimated that <i>Mom and Dad</i> had taken in $8 million from twenty million moviegoers. And publicity issuing from <i>Mom and Dad</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s production company indicated that by the end of 1956 it had grossed over $80 million worldwide. Net rentals of around $22 million by 1956 would easily place it in the top ten films of the late 1940s and early 1950s had it appeared on conventional lists. Some estimates have placed its total gross over the years at up to $100 million, and it was still playing drive-in dates into 1975...The film was made for around $65,000 with a crew of Hollywood veterans including director William "One Shot" Beaudine, cinematographer Marcel LePicard, and a cast that sported old stalwarts Hardie Albright, Francis Ford, and John Hamilton.</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=%22Bold%21+Daring%21+Shocking%21+True%21%22%3A+A+History+of+Exploitation+Films%2C+1919%E2%80%931959&amp;rft.pages=197-199&amp;rft.pub=Duke+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8223-2374-7&amp;rft.aulast=Schaefer&amp;rft.aufirst=Eric&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
</li>

"Production Cost: $1.6 (Unadjusted $s in Millions of $s)"</li>

<li id="cite_note-212"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-212">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222" rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style"/><cite class="citation book cs1" id="CITEREFGabler2007">Gabler, Neal (2007). <i>Walt Disney: the biography</i>. <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Aurum_Press" title="Aurum Press">Aurum Press</a>. pp. <a class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=EX0WAQAAIAAJ&amp;q=%22song+of+the+south%22+%22million%22" rel="nofollow">438</a>. <q>Still, the film wound up grossing $3.3 million...</q></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Walt+Disney%3A+the+biography&amp;rft.pages=438&amp;rft.pub=Aurum+Press&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.aulast=Gabler&amp;rft.aufirst=Neal&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AList+of+highest-grossing+films"></span></span>
